irca 1150","1224":"1224","1100":"1100","about 1164":"circa 1164","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1120–":"about 1120–Deceased","1120–Male":"1120–Deceased","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1132–1161":"1132–1161","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1142–Male":"1142–Deceased","1149–Male":"1149–Deceased","1142–Female":"1142–Deceased","1150–1186":"1150–1186","1161–Male":"1161–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1095–Male":"1095–Deceased","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","about 1161":"about 1161","1190":"1190","1132":"1132","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1186":"1186","1142":"1142","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1095":"1095","1161":"1161","Abt 1120":"about 1120","1215":"1215","1149":"1149","Abt 1150":"about 1150","1224":"1224","1100":"1100","about 1164":"about 1164","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":95,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in